# CSRD MATLAB Conventions

## 1. structs are value types - mutating helpers MUST return them

MATLAB structs are passed by value. A helper that "modifies" a struct without returning it
silently throws the change away.

```matlab
% BAD - caller never sees the antenna upgrade
function updateAntennaConfig(TxInfo, segments)
    TxInfo.NumTransmitAntennas = segments{end}.NumTransmitAntennas;
end

% GOOD
function TxInfo = updateAntennaConfig(TxInfo, segments)
    TxInfo.NumTransmitAntennas = segments{end}.NumTransmitAntennas;
end
```

Class instances (`matlab.System`, `handle`) are reference types - mutating them in-place is fine.

## 2. System object lifecycle - reset RNG when reusing cached instances

Cached `matlab.System` objects retain their internal RNG state across `step()` calls. If a
test or pipeline expects deterministic output for a fixed `Seed`, either:
- create a fresh instance per call, or
- explicitly `release(obj); setup(obj, ...)` before each `step`.

Calling `step` twice on the same cached `RandomBit` with the same `Seed` does NOT produce
the same bits the second time.

## 3. Complex signals: `samples x antennas`, column-major

All baseband / RF signals are `numSamples x numAntennas` complex doubles. Multi-antenna
processing iterates over columns. Do not transpose silently; channel/RF blocks assume the
first dimension is time.

## 4. Random streams - prefer named seeded streams for reproducibility

```matlab
% GOOD
obj.pRandomStream = RandStream('mt19937ar', 'Seed', obj.Seed);
realNoise = randn(obj.pRandomStream, size(signalData));
```

Document the `Seed` property; expose it as a public, settable property for any block that
generates random samples. Accept legacy aliases (`SeedValue` -> `Seed`) in factories so
older configs do not silently fall back to the default seed.

## 5. Property access for testability

Internal handles that tests need to inspect (e.g. `MemoryLessNonlinearity`,
`SampleShifter`) should be `properties (GetAccess = public, SetAccess = protected)`.
Pure-protected blocks force tests to subclass or hack `struct(obj)`, both of which are
maintenance traps.

## 6. Avoid `try ... catch <swallow>` without identifier filtering

Generic `catch ME end` blocks hide both transient noise and serious physics errors.
Always look at `ME.identifier` and either rethrow scenario-skip identifiers (see
`csrd-architecture.mdc` rule 4) or log + classify the error.
